Collecting contemporary art is all about riding a knife=E2=80=99s edge. On =
one side, you=E2=80=99re finding the next new talent ahead of everyone else=
; on the other, you=E2=80=99re out of step, or worse, clueless about what=
=E2=80=99s coming next. Museum exhibitions are the coin of the realm in con=
temporary art, and the Institute of Contemporary Art Miami prides itself on=
 exhibiting the works of emerging artists before anyone else. Today, as col=
lectors stream into Miami for Art Week, the design district venue will open=
 shows by Ding Shilun, Marguerite Humeau, and Lucy Bull. These join the fir=
st solo U.S. museum exhibition of work by recently deceased Japanese pop ar=
tist Keiichi Tanaami.

When I was in Dallas, in November, I saw Bull and Humeau pop up repeatedly =
in a number of different collectors=E2=80=99 homes. Validating collectors=
=E2=80=99
tastes isn=E2=80=99t necessarily ICA Miami director Alex Gartenfeld=E2=80=
=99s goal, but it doesn=E2=80=99t hurt to be early and on trend, especially=
 in Miami, where collecting contemporary art is a contact sport. =E2=80=9CT=
here=E2=80=99s a tremendous audience for, history of, and engagement with, =
contemporary art in Miami,=E2=80=9D the 38-year-old director explained to m=
e last week. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a really wide lane for institutions l=
ike ours to do =E2=80=98cutting-edge contemporary=E2=80=99 that has a globa=
l perspective, obviously, with a particular lens on the Western Hemisphere,=
 Global South, and Miami, but really kind of a global agenda.=E2=80=9D

Over the past few years, Gartenfeld has mounted early and notable museum sh=
ows for artists like Sasha Gordon, Charles Gaines, Claire Tabouret, Avery S=
inger, Nina Chanel Abney, Hugh Hayden, and Jad=C3=A9 Fadojutimi. There have=
 also been retrospectives on the work of Judy Chicago, Huguette Caland,
Michel Majerus, Denzil Forrester, and Allan McCollum. Gartenfeld is less in=
terested in capturing the moment and more focused on leading a search party=
 into the future. =E2=80=9COur real benchmark, rather than being in any zei=
tgeist,=E2=80=9D he told me, is creating =E2=80=9Cfirst institutional platf=
orms for exhibition.=E2=80=9D

Miami=E2=80=99s New Collectors

Many of ICA Miami=E2=80=99s exhibitions came about because the museum acqui=
red work by these artists very early. =E2=80=9CWe have been, in many cases,=
 unafraid,=E2=80=9D Gartenfeld said, =E2=80=9Cto be the first institution t=
o collect, which has been, I=E2=80=99d say, advantageous for a museum that =
doesn=E2=80=99t have unlimited resources.=E2=80=9D

The ability of a decade-old museum to acquire work at all, let alone before=
 other institutions and collectors, requires a large and engaged board. And=
, indeed, Gartenfeld=E2=80=99s true masterstroke was an ability to position=
 ICA Miami at the center of the city=E2=80=99s collecting community, acting=
 as both a common context and a coordinating council among its affluent col=
lectors. =E2=80=9CI guess it is all about community building,=E2=80=9D Gart=
enfeld said. =E2=80=9CIn the last decade, there=E2=80=99s been a major perc=
eptual flip on Miami as a serious cultural anchor.
And that wasn=E2=80=99t incidental.=E2=80=9D

Put simply, the growth in the city=E2=80=99s cultural infrastructure came a=
bout because Miami decided to take itself more seriously. But Gartenfeld be=
lieves that the foundation was laid long before that via Miami=E2=80=99s =
=E2=80=9Cdeep bench=E2=80=9D of collectors dating back to the Cisneros, Rub=
ell, Margulies, de la Cruz, and Braman families=E2=80=94the very locus of a=
ctivity that brought Art Basel to Miami Beach two decades ago.

Gartenfeld has spent the last 11 years working closely with local collector=
s through the city and the art scene=E2=80=99s evolution. =E2=80=9CThe coll=
ections that they=E2=80=99ve built are truly accomplished and extraordinary=
,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThey just happen to be in private places. And =
we=E2=80=99ve tried to demonstrate how those great collections can effectiv=
ely collaborate with the institutions. I think that=E2=80=99s a key stage o=
f growth in the city. I do think that we=E2=80=99ve been exemplary at doing=
 that and
presenting that collaboration.=E2=80=9D

A Dealmaker With an Eye

Gartenfeld=E2=80=99s skill at coordinating a diverse and even bumptious col=
lecting community came into stark relief earlier this autumn when he announ=
ced that the ICA Miami would acquire, for $25 million, a building just step=
s away on the same block that previously housed the de la Cruz Collection. =
Rosa de la Cruz, the driving force behind the collection, died in February =
at the age of 81, and her family has moved quickly to wind up her long hist=
ory as a leader of Miami=E2=80=99s art-obsessed collectors.

This expansion will give Gartenfeld as much exhibition space as New York=E2=
=80=99s Whitney Museum, all in the heart of Miami=E2=80=99s trendiest distr=
ict. Craig Robins, the developer behind the design district, was also instr=
umental in bringing the de la Cruzes to the area 15 years ago. Robins and C=
arlos de la Cruz had dreamed of the ICA
Miami taking over the collection space, but someone had to make it all happ=
en. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve been wanting to do this for close to five years,=
=E2=80=9D Gartenfeld said.

=E2=80=9CAlex was brilliant in putting the deal together,=E2=80=9D Robins t=
old me in a phone interview, reminding me that even at a bargain price, Gar=
tenfeld and the ICA Miami board still had to rally and come up with serious=
 money for the building and renovations. =E2=80=9CHe said he would do it, a=
nd he did it early.=E2=80=9D

This wasn=E2=80=99t the first time that Gartenfeld had impressed Robins. Th=
ey met a decade ago, just after Gartenfeld settled in town for a curator=E2=
=80=99s job at MoCA North Miami. At the same time, Robins had hatched a pla=
n with Norman and Irma Braman to build a museum in the design district: He =
would provide land, and the Bramans would fund the museum. Gartenfeld=E2=80=
=99s ability to solve problems at MoCA North Miami impressed Robins. =E2=80=
=9CI saw how talented he was in that moment,=E2=80=9D he remembered. And
in addition to steering the ICA Miami into its home in the design district,=
 Gartenfeld also gave Robins advice on emerging artists to collect. =E2=80=
=9CHe=E2=80=99s brilliant and resourceful,=E2=80=9D Robins said, and =E2=80=
=9Chas real capability as a director, plus an incredible eye.=E2=80=9D

Gartenfeld is looking to spend the next year planning renovations to the ne=
w building and envisioning the launch. ICA Miami has a collection of its ow=
n that is rarely on view due to limitations of space and programming. His c=
urators and board members are also actively collecting. And though he views=
 the last five to seven years as =E2=80=9Cthe largest amount of high-qualit=
y work by emerging artists that=E2=80=99s maybe ever been produced in a per=
iod,=E2=80=9D he also admits =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re in a different part of =
the art-consumption cycle than we had been previously.=E2=80=9D There=E2=80=
=99s a lot of art to digest amid rapid cultural change.

While I was speaking to Robins about Gartenfeld, I raised a sensitive issue=
: With several
prominent museums looking for new directors, was Robins worried about losin=
g him? The response was quite gracious. Robins admits that it makes no sens=
e to stand in the way of opportunity, but he also felt confident that Garte=
nfeld was committed to Miami and had several more years to see out his ambi=
tious plans. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s absolutely brilliant on many fronts,=E2=
=80=9D Robins said, =E2=80=9Cone of the most impressive people in the art w=
orld.=E2=80=9D

Endnotes=E2=80=A6

I had a last-minute personal conflict that forced me to cancel my plans for=
 Miami. If you=E2=80=99re down there, please drop me a note to say what you=
 think is interesting, who you saw, or where you had a good time. I really =
do want to hear from you.

I was looking forward to stopping in at the Rubell Museum, still going stro=
ng, to see the work of Vanessa Raw, their most recent artist in residence. =
I was also curious about Rachel Feinstein at The Bass Museum; Calida Rawles=
 at the P=C3=A9rez Art Museum Miami; and Katarina Caserman at Marquez Art P=
rojects.

What else did you see?

Let me know so I can share with the rest of the class on Sunday.
