x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Collecting contempo=
rary art is all about riding a knife=E2=80=99s edge. On one side, you=E2=80=
=99re finding the next new talent ahead of everyone else; on the other, you=
=E2=80=99re out of step, or worse, clueless about what=E2=80=99s coming nex=
t. Museum exhibitions are the coin of the realm in contemporary art, and th=
e Institute of Contemporary Art Miami prides itself on exhibiting the works=
 of emerging artists before anyone else. Today, as collectors stream into M=
iami for Art Week, the design district venue will open shows by <b>Ding Shi=
lun</b>, <b>Marguerite Humeau</b>, and <b>Lucy Bull</b>. These join the fir=
st solo U.S. museum exhibition of work by recently deceased Japanese pop ar=
tist <b>Keiichi Tanaami</b>. <br/><br/>When I was in Dallas, in November, I=
 saw Bull and Humeau pop up <i>repeatedly</i> in a number of different coll=
ectors=E2=80=99 homes. Validating collectors=E2=80=99
tastes isn=E2=80=99t necessarily ICA Miami director <b>Alex</b> <b>Gartenfe=
ld</b>=E2=80=99s goal, but it doesn=E2=80=99t hurt to be early and on trend=
, especially in Miami, where collecting contemporary art is a contact sport=
=2E =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a tremendous aud=
ience for, history of, and engag=
ement with, contemporary art in Miami,=E2=80=9D the 38-year-old director ex=
plained to me last week. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a really wide lane for in=
stitutions like ours to do =E2=80=98cutting-edge contemporary=E2=80=99 that=
 has a global perspective, obviously, with a particular lens on the Western=
 Hemisphere, Global South, and Miami, but really kind of a global agenda.=
=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Over the past few years, Gartenfeld has mounted early a=
nd notable museum shows for artists like <b>Sasha Gordon</b>, <b>Charles Ga=
ines</b>, <b>Claire Tabouret</b>, <b>Avery Singer</b>, <b>Nina Chanel Abney=
</b>, <b>Hugh Hayden</b>, and <b>Jad=C3=A9 Fadojutimi</b>. There have also =
been retrospectives on the work of <b>Judy Chicago</b>, <b>Huguette Caland<=
/b>,
<b>Michel Majerus</b>, <b>Denzil Forrester</b>, and <b>Allan McCollum</b>. =
Gartenfeld is less interested in capturing the moment and more focused on l=
eading a search party into the future. =E2=80=9COur real benchmark, rather =
than being in any zeitgeist,=E2=80=9D he told me, is creating =E2=80=9Cfirs=
t institutional platforms for exhibition.=E2=80=9D<br/></td>
