          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Gartenfeld=E2=80=99=
s skill at coordinating a diverse and even bumptious collecting community c=
ame into stark relief earlier this autumn when he announced that the ICA Mi=
ami would acquire, for $25 million, a building just steps away on the same =
block that previously housed the de la Cruz Collection. <b>Rosa de la Cruz<=
/b>, the driving force behind the collection, died in February at the age o=
f 81, and her family has moved quickly to wind up her long history as a lea=
der of Miami=E2=80=99s art-obsessed collectors. <br/><br/>This expansion wi=
ll give Gartenfeld as much exhibition space as New York=E2=80=99s Whitney M=
useum, all in the heart of Miami=E2=80=99s trendiest district. <b>Craig Rob=
ins</b>, the developer behind the design district, was also instrumental in=
 bringing the de la Cruzes to the area 15 years ago. Robins and <b>Carlos d=
e la Cruz</b> had dreamed of the ICA
Miami taking over the collection space, but someone had to make it all happ=
en. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve been wanting to do this for close to five years,=
=E2=80=9D Gartenfeld said.<br/><br/>=E2=80=9CAlex was brilliant in putting =
the deal together,=E2=80=9D Robins told me in a phone interview, reminding =
me that even at a bargain price, Gartenfeld and the ICA Miami board still h=
ad to rally and come up with serious money for the building and renovations=
=2E =E2=80=9CHe said he would do it, an=
d he did it early.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>T=
his wasn=E2=80=99t the first time that Gartenfeld had impressed Robins. The=
y met a decade ago, just after Gartenfeld settled in town for a curator=E2=
=80=99s job at MoCA North Miami. At the same time, Robins had hatched a pla=
n with <b>Norman</b> and <b>Irma Braman</b> to build a museum in the design=
 district: He would provide land, and the Bramans would fund the museum. Ga=
rtenfeld=E2=80=99s ability to solve problems at MoCA North Miami impressed =
Robins. =E2=80=9CI saw how talented he was in that moment,=E2=80=9D he reme=
mbered. And
in addition to steering the ICA Miami into its home in the design district,=
 Gartenfeld also gave Robins advice on emerging artists to collect. =E2=80=
=9CHe=E2=80=99s brilliant and resourceful,=E2=80=9D Robins said, and =E2=80=
=9Chas real capability as a director, plus an incredible eye.=E2=80=9D <br/=
><br/>Gartenfeld is looking to spend the next year planning renovations to =
the new building and envisioning the launch. ICA Miami has a collection of =
its own that is rarely on view due to limitations of space and programming.=
 His curators and board members are also actively collecting. And though he=
 views the last five to seven years as =E2=80=9Cthe largest amount of high-=
quality work by emerging artists that=E2=80=99s maybe ever been produced in=
 a period,=E2=80=9D he also admits =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re in a different pa=
rt of the art-consumption cycle than we had been previously.=E2=80=9D There=
=E2=80=99s a lot of art to digest amid rapid cultural change. <br/><br/>Whi=
le I was speaking to Robins about Gartenfeld, I raised a sensitive issue: W=
ith several
prominent museums looking for new directors, was Robins worried about losin=
g him? The response was quite gracious. Robins admits that it makes no sens=
e to stand in the way of opportunity, but he also felt confident that Garte=
nfeld was committed to Miami and had several more years to see out his ambi=
tious plans. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s absolutely brilliant on many fronts,=E2=
=80=9D Robins said, =E2=80=9Cone of the most impressive people in the art w=
orld.=E2=80=9D <br/></td>
         </tr>
